40|$|Does violent {{repression}} {{strengthen the}} state? In this {{paper we explore}} the legacies of repression by the Mexican government on subsequent state consolidation. We investigate how a particular form of state repression, <b>forced</b> <b>disappearances</b> of alleged leftist dissidents, during the 1960 s and 1970 s in Mexico had path-dependent consequences for different dimensions of state capacity nearly fifty years later. To do so, we rely on data gathered from suppressed Mexican human rights reports of <b>forced</b> <b>disappearances</b> which, to our knowledge, have not been analyzed by social scientists before. Controlling for a rich set of pre-disappearances covariates, we find that <b>forced</b> <b>disappearances</b> are positively correlated with contemporary measures of fiscal and bureaucratic capacity. However, historical <b>forced</b> <b>disappearances</b> do not help the state to provide security, to consolidate its monopoly {{over the use of}} force, or to provide welfare-related public goods in the long run. Moreover, disappearances are negatively correlated with various measures of trust in the government...|$|R
